aa(lp40
VBut today, the way I want you to understand a black hole,
p41
aVfor the proof of a black hole,
p42
aVis to think of it as an object
p43
aVwhose mass is confined to zero volume.
p44
aVSo, despite the fact that I'm going to talk to you about
p45
aVan object that's supermassive,
p46
aVand I'm going to get to what that really means in a moment,
p47
aVit has no finite size.
p48
aVSo, this is a little tricky.
p49
aa(lp50
VBut fortunately there is a finite size that you can see,
p51
aVand that's known as the Schwarzschild radius.
p52
aVAnd that's named after the guy who recognized
p53
aVwhy it was such an important radius.
p54
aVThis is a virtual radius, not reality; the black hole has no size.
p55
aVSo why is it so important?
p56
aVIt's important because it tells us
p57
aVthat any object can become a black hole.
p58
aVThat means you, your neighbor, your cellphone,
p59
aVthe auditorium can become a black hole
p60
aVif you can figure out how to compress it down
p61
aVto the size of the Schwarzschild radius.
p62
aa(lp63
VAt that point, what's going to happen?
p64
aVAt that point gravity wins.
p65
aVGravity wins over all other known forces.
p66
aVAnd the object is forced to continue to collapse
p67
aVto an infinitely small object.
p68
aVAnd then it's a black hole.
p69
aVSo, if I were to compress the Earth down to the size of a sugar cube,
p70
aVit would become a black hole,
p71
aVbecause the size of a sugar cube is its Schwarzschild radius.
