aa(lp73
VNow, the key here is to figure out what that Schwarzschild radius is.
p74
aVAnd it turns out that it's actually pretty simple to figure out.
p75
aVIt depends only on the mass of the object.
p76
aVBigger objects have bigger Schwarzschild radii.
p77
aVSmaller objects have smaller Schwarzschild radii.
p78
aVSo, if I were to take the sun
p79
aVand compress it down to the scale of the University of Oxford,
p80
aVit would become a black hole.
p81
aa(lp82
VSo, now we know what a Schwarzschild radius is.
p83
aVAnd it's actually quite a useful concept,
p84
aVbecause it tells us not only
p85
aVwhen a black hole will form,
p86
aVbut it also gives us the key elements for the proof of a black hole.
p87
aVI only need two things.
p88
aVI need to understand the mass of the object
p89
aVI'm claiming is a black hole,
p90
aVand what its Schwarzschild radius is.
p91
aVAnd since the mass determines the Schwarzschild radius,
p92
aVthere is actually only one thing I really need to know.
